'''Peter Diamond''' ([[August 10]], [[1920s#1929]] &ndash; [[March 27]], [[2004]]) was the stunt coordinator on [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|Episodes IV]]<ref name="ANH" /> and [[Star Wars: Episode V The Empire Strikes Back|V]],<ref name="ESB">{{Film|V}}</ref> and assisted with stunts on [[Star Wars: Episode VI Return of the Jedi|Episode VI]]. He created the [[lightsaber combat]] styles of [[Form V|Djem So]] and [[Form III|Soresu]] for [[Luke Skywalker]], [[Anakin Skywalker|Darth Vader]] and [[Obi-Wan Kenobi]].
==Biography==
[[File:PeterDiamond-MOSW.png|thumb|left|210x210px|Peter Diamond, during the filming of ''A New Hope''.]]
He also played [[A'Koba]], [[Garouf Lafoe]], a [[TK-119|stormtrooper]], a [[Death Star Trooper]] named [[Corporal]] [[Prescott]] in the [[Star Wars Legends|Legends]] continuity, a [[Cold weather assault trooper|snowtrooper]], a [[scout trooper]], [[Unidentified Weequay Skiff Master|a Weequay skiff master]], and a [[Rebel Alliance Special Forces|rebel commando]] in a subsequently deleted scene.

[[File:PeterDiamond-Lightman.jpg|thumb|right|210x210px|Peter Diamond, With [[Anthony Daniels]] in as a Light Bulb Creature in ''Return of the Jedi''.]]
Additionally, he wore a black suit covered with lightbulbs inside Jabba's Palace that was to be transformed into a creature in post production, however the idea was scrapped and never fully realized.<ref name="Inside Story">''[[I Am C-3PO: The Inside Story]]''</ref>

[[File:PeterDiamond-CII.jpg|thumb|left|210x210px|Peter Diamond at the [[Celebration II|Star Wars Celebration II]].]]
Unfortunately in Indianapolis during the [[Celebration II|Star Wars Celebration II]] Peter Diamond  is shown holding a custom commemorative plaque presented to him by the [[501st Legion]] to honor his induction as an Honorary Member. Diamond, who famously portrayed numerous characters including the [[Tusken Raider]] that attacked [[Luke Skywalker]] and the "cantina snitch" [[Garouf Lafoe]], was recognized at the event for his extensive contributions as the "[[Stormtrooper|original Stormtrooper]]" and stunt master.

He was among the people interviewed for the documentary ''[[Empire of Dreams: The Story of the Star Wars Trilogy]]'', which was released six months after his death.
